# Command & Conquer Generals Zero Hour - Headless Engine Architecture Documentation

## Executive Summary

The C&C Generals Zero Hour (GeneralsMD) source code is a complex Win32-based RTS engine with clearly separated game logic and rendering layers. The codebase uses a modular architecture with subsystem initialization, making it feasible to build a headless engine by stubbing out rendering/audio components and focusing on the core GameLogic and GameEngine systems.

---

## 1. TOP-LEVEL STRUCTURE

### Directory Organization

```
cczh-source-code/
├── Generals/               # Original C&C Generals (v1.0)
│   └── Code/
│       ├── GameEngine/    # Core game logic (platform-agnostic)
│       ├── GameEngineDevice/  # Rendering/audio (platform-specific)
│       ├── Main/          # Windows entry point
│       ├── Libraries/      # Third-party dependencies
│       └── Tools/         # Development tools
│
├── GeneralsMD/            # Zero Hour expansion (MD = MajorDestruction era)
│   └── Code/              # Identical structure to Generals/
│
└── Run/                   # Output binaries directory
```

### Generals vs GeneralsMD

- **Generals**: Original game (v1.0, ~2003)
- **GeneralsMD**: Zero Hour expansion, same code structure, differences in:
  - Map data and unit templates (INI files, not source code)
  - Game balance tweaks
  - New units/buildings specific to Zero Hour

**Both share identical source code architecture.**

---

## 2. GAMEENGINE MODULES (Core Game Logic)

### Directory Structure: `Code/GameEngine/Source/` and `Code/GameEngine/Include/`

```
GameEngine/
├── Source/
│   ├── Common/          # Shared utilities, game state, configuration
│   │   ├── Audio/
│   │   ├── Bezier/
│   │   ├── INI/         # Configuration file parsing
│   │   ├── RTS/         # High-level game concepts (Teams, Squads)
│   │   ├── System/      # Global managers (Radar, BuildAssistant, Upgrade)
│   │   └── Thing/       # Object templates and factories
│   │
│   ├── GameClient/      # Client-side simulation (UI, camera, input handling)
│   │   ├── Drawable/    # Visual representation layer
│   │   ├── GUI/         # Control bar, menus, UI callbacks
│   │   ├── Input/       # Keyboard/mouse input processing
│   │   ├── MessageStream/  # Message routing
│   │   ├── System/      # Display, particles, sounds
│   │   └── Terrain/     # Terrain visual system
│   │
│   ├── GameLogic/       # *** CORE GAME SIMULATION (CRITICAL FOR HEADLESS) ***
│   │   ├── AI/          # AI player logic, pathfinding, group management
│   │   ├── Object/      # Units, buildings, projectiles (Object class)
│   │   ├── Map/         # Terrain logic, triggers
│   │   ├── ScriptEngine/  # Map scripting (custom game logic)
│   │   └── System/      # GameLogic singleton, state management
│   │
│   ├── GameNetwork/     # Network multiplayer, command distribution
│   │   ├── GameSpy/     # Online matchmaking
│   │   └── WOLBrowser/  # Web browser integration
│   │
│   └── Precompiled/     # Precompiled headers
│
└── Include/
    ├── Common/          # Header files (parallel structure)
    ├── GameClient/
    ├── GameLogic/
    └── GameNetwork/
```

### Key Files in GameEngine

| File | Purpose | Location |
|------|---------|----------|
| **GameCommon.h** | **Frame rate & game constants** | `Include/Common/` |
| **GameEngine.h** | Main engine interface, `execute()` loop | `Include/Common/` |
| **GameLogic.h** | Game state manager, object registry | `Include/GameLogic/` |
| **Object.h** | Base entity class (units/buildings) | `Include/GameLogic/` |
| **Player.h** | Player state (money, power, supplies) | `Include/Common/` |
| **Money.h** | Resource tracking | `Include/Common/` |
| **PartitionManager.h** | Spatial partitioning & fog of war | `Include/GameLogic/` |
| **MessageStream.h** | Event/command propagation system | `Include/Common/` |
| **NetCommandMsg.h** | Multiplayer command serialization | `Include/GameNetwork/` |
| **UpdateModule.h** | Base class for unit/building behaviors | `Include/GameLogic/Module/` |

---

## 3. KEY SYSTEMS FOR HEADLESS ENGINE

### 3.1 Game Tick / Main Loop

**Frame Rate Definition:**
```cpp
// File: Code/GameEngine/Include/Common/GameCommon.h (Line 66)
enum {
    LOGICFRAMES_PER_SECOND = 30,      // *** 30 FPS fixed tick rate ***
    MSEC_PER_SECOND = 1000
};
```

**Main Loop Entry Points:**

```cpp
// GameEngine class hierarchy:
// File: Code/GameEngine/Include/Common/GameEngine.h

class GameEngine : public SubsystemInterface {
    void init(int argc, char *argv[]);     // Initialize
    void reset();                            // Reset to start state
    void execute();                          // Main loop (blocks until quit)
    void update();                           // Per-frame update
    void setFramesPerSecondLimit(Int fps);  // Cap FPS (default 45)
};
```

**Game Loop Architecture:**
1. `GameEngine::execute()` - Main loop (Win32-specific in `Win32GameEngine`)
2. Each frame:
   - `GameEngine::update()` calls
   - `GameLogic::update()` - Update all units/buildings
   - `GameClient::update()` - Update camera, input, UI
   - `Display::draw()` - Render scene
3. Loop continues until `GameEngine::getQuitting()` returns true

**File:** `Code/GameEngine/Source/Common/GameEngine.cpp`

**For headless operation:**
- Call `GameLogic::update()` directly in your own loop
- Stub out `GameClient` and `Display` initialization
- Use fixed 30 Hz tick rate (no frame-skipping sync needed)

---

### 3.2 Entity/Object System

**Base Class Hierarchy:**

```cpp
// File: Code/GameEngine/Include/Common/Thing.h
class Thing : public MemoryPoolObject {
